Karolina Kowalkiewicz (116) vs.
Julia Polastri (116) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Polastri (-450), Kowalkiewicz (+350) Round 1 Strawweights take center stage as the prelims roll on.
With a 12-year youth advantage on her side, a win for Polastri (13-5, 1-2 UFC) would lead her to a .500 record in the Octagon while dumping Kowalkiewicz (16-9, 9-9 UFC) below that threshold.
A chasm of high-level experience separates the two, but it is "Psycho" who will serve as a significant betting favorite.
The two ladies will be joined in the cage by referee Marc Goddard, who clocks them in as they clap hands.
Kowalkiewicz takes right to the center of the cage, and as booming chants of "Uh Vai Morrer" rain down, Polastri flashes a wry grin.
The ladies toss out low kicks, and Kowalkiewicz strings together a combination ending with a left hand.
Polastri resets and pitches a leg kick, only for Kowalkiewicz to counter over the top.
Kowalkiewicz rips a body kick in the midst of her strike combos, and Polastri is not a fan and fires back with one much heavier.
The former title challenger grimaces from the strike to her midsection, and Polastri explodes into a flurry of punches and kicks.
Kowalkiewicz protects herself against the wire, and she smiles when Polastri peels back.
The smile quickly turns to a frown when Polastri drives a knee home to the body, but she is able to back off and shake it off.
Kowalkiewicz throws a kick, changes stances and works the body.
Kowalkiewicz slips a punch and connects with a right, and she takes a few on the chin to hit the Brazilian back.
Kowalkiewicz spins with a back fist, and it collides into the guard but she is not far enough away to avoid counters.
Kowalkiewicz thinks about a trip takedown when catching one of Polastri's kicks, but she lets the limb down where there is nothing to it.
Polastri again tries to tie up the Polish woman, where she spams knees to what might be an already compromised midsection.
Polastri goes over the top with an elbow, and she uses her weight to press Kowalkiewicz on the fencing.
Kowalkiewicz gives her back a few knees and elbows to think about, forcing a break.
Kowalkiewicz whiffs on the subsequent spinning back fist.
A front kick from her does split the guard, and any cheers from her corner are completely drowned out from the chants of the crowd.
They trade heavy blows while standing right in the pocket, with Polastri appearing to have the power advantage and the superior speed too.
Kowalkiewicz feebly spins when under fire, and Polastri lays into her with an onslaught of punches that knock the former KSW fighter into the wall.
As Polastri keeps connecting, the bell sounds.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Polastri Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Polastri Tyler Treese scores the round: 10-9 Polastri Round 2 They clap hands again to start off the second stanza, and some swelling has developed under Kowalkiewicz' right eye.
She pays it no mind as Polastri comes right at her throwing caution to the wind.
Kowalkiewicz tries to take her off her feet with a takedown attempt, but Polastri shuts it down and punches her square in the face.
Kowalkiewicz meanders forward to grapple again, and Polastri's intercepting knee and uppercut shut that down.
Polastri senses that Kowalkiewicz is struggling, and she walks her foe down and beats on her relentlessly.
Kowalkiewicz bounds off the fence to reset, and Polastri drops her hands and takes several deep breaths to get her wind back from going all-out.
Kowalkiewicz is tough as nails, and she takes advantage of this opening with distant strikes.
Once Polastri is ready to engage again, she raises her hands and cracks the Polish woman.
Polastri fearlessly approaches her opponent, even with her energy reserves far from full, and she welcomes striking exchanges.
Kowalkiewicz puts volume together as Polastri is looking for big power blows, and although Kowalkiewicz takes some on the chin, she evades the worst of the blowsâ¦until she doesn't.
Totally unafraid of anything that comes back at her, Polastri connects with a flurry of punches and kicks that knock Kowalkiewicz back to the wall again.
When Kowalkiewicz tries to get away, Polastri raises her arms in the air to further lather up the ravenous audience.
Kowalkiewicz attempts a takedown, and Polastri takes longer to stop it but still manages to stonewall the former title challenger.
Polastri flashes out a jab directly on the swollen cheek, and Kowalkiewicz kicks her back in the body.
Polastri slaps her midsection, and she walks through the potshots of Kowalkiewicz to land heavy punches that bust open Kowalkiewicz' nose.
Kowalkiewicz spins with an elbow that bangs off the forehead, and Polastri energizes herself into one final assault before the round concludes.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Polastri Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Polastri Tyler Treese scores the round: 10-9 Polastri Round 3 After 10 minutes of action, the strawweights come together in the center of the cage to hug it out.
Polastri lands a single power strike, and Kowalkiewicz lets her have it with a long, effective flurry of fists and feet.
Kowalkiewicz swings and ducks away to evade counters, and Polastri is still sporadically swinging for the bleachers.
Kowalkiewicz sticks her foe with a short right hand, and she stuns the Brazilian for a second with another scooping uppercut.
Polastri steels herself and boots Kowalkiewicz upside the head, and that only spurs Kowalkiewicz into more activity with a lengthy stretch of punches.
Polastri connects with a hard body shot, and Kowalkiewicz' body language and expression changes.
Polastri digs several more strikes to the torso, and Kowalkiewicz bends over to try to take some of the sting out of them and has to actually sprint away to fully reset.
Polastri walks her down like a Terminator, and her punches have developed more swelling and damage on Kowalkiewicz' face.
With a full head of steam, Polastri steps in with a booming head kick that shakes up the ex-title challenger.
Putting Kowalkiewicz' on ice skates, Polastri marches forward and delivers a ruthless combination of punches to the head and body that have Kowalkiewicz in all sorts of trouble.
With a couple minute still left on the clock, Polastri is cognizant that she does not want to punch herself out, but she knows that Kowalkiewicz is in trouble."
Psycho" lets loose with all of her remaining energy, busting up Kowalkiewicz further and knocking her head around like a speed bag.

As Kowalkiewicz is barely on her feet, possibly because the cage is behind her, Goddard intervenes to save the Polish woman from her toughness.The crowd goes wild for the first Brazilian tonight to beat a foreign opponent, and Polastri hands Kowalkiewicz her second knockout lossâthe first came from the mighty fist of Jessica Andrade.
That is good company to be in.
The Official Result Julia Polastri def.
Karolina Kowalkiewicz R3 2:56 via TKO (Head Kick and Punches)
Stewart Nicoll (126) vs.

Lucas Rocha (126) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Rocha (-130); Nicoll (+110) Round 1 The first of two men with the nickname of "Fenomeno" enters the cage in a flyweight affair where someone's sophomore effort will go far better than their respective debut.
In a surprisingly clever bit of matchmaking, both Rocha (17-2, 0-1 UFC) and Nicoll (8-1, 0-1 UFC) suffered their first loss in the UFC last year by technical submission.
Someone might get put to sleep in this one, so referee Jason Herzog is on his A-game for it.
The 125ers tap their gloves together to get going.
Rocha goes right after the Aussie, testing the waters with an overhand right to gauge his range.
Nicoll throws back several punches that are too far away, and Rocha responds it with a takedown shot.
He bounces off Nicoll's chest and gets back into striking range.
Nicoll chips at the front leg, and he points at the spot he struck.
Rocha ignores him and pops him in the chops with a pair of punches.
Both men land single hooks, and Nicoll's left eye is starting to show some damage less than 90 seconds in.
Rocha pounds the body with a kick, and he lets Nicoll try to take him down as the Aussie falls on his face.
He gets up smiling, as "Fenomeno" is stone-faced and ready to keep trading hands.
Nicoll spins with a clean back kick, and Rocha is surprised by the blow and needs a moment to get his bearings.
With Nicoll backing up, Rocha aims a right hand to the body, and Nicoll hits the deck to take the sting out of it.
Popping back up, he goes right back to slinging two-punch combinations at his foe until he can shoot on the hips.
The Aussie completes the takedown, only for Rocha to power back up to his feet within seconds.
Nicoll keeps his grip around the waist from behind, imposing his weight to try to drag Rocha down from behind.
Nicoll gets off a cheeky knee to the jaw with Rocha's hands down, but the hands alone are not enough to be a grounded fighter so Herzog tells them to play on.
Rocha drops to a knee to protect from further blows, and Nicoll tries to wrestle him down but is shut down.
Rocha walks him down and cracks him with an uppercut, and Nicoll grins like a banshee and backpedals.
Rocha loads up on big right hands, and Nicoll takes part of one on the side of the head.
As they clash together, Rocha spins with a hook kick as Nicoll comes at him.
Nicoll tries to dive after a takedown, and "Fenomeno" pushes him to the floor and backs off to make him stand up.
Nicoll immediately shoots for a double-leg takedown, and Rocha backs himself to the wall and leapfrogs over the back of his foe to defend it.
Nicoll still manages to wrangle him to a knee, and the round concludes.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Rocha Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Rocha Tyler Treese scores the round: 10-9 Rocha Round 2 Rocha starts off the round a man possessed, connecting with punches and a body kick before twirling around.
Herzog tells the fighters in Portuguese to watch out for eye pokes, and Rocha closes his fist and slams it repeatedly into Nicoll's face.
Nicoll responds with a takedown shot that Rocha laughs off as he is nowhere to be found, and he lets Nicoll stand so he can complete multiple combinations.
Nicoll is tough but constantly under fire, and his shots have little setup and do not go far.
Meanwhile, Rocha's scooping uppercut continues to split the guard, and he draws out a takedown shot to push Nicoll on his back.
Nicoll lays there, as if to say "step into my parlor, said the spider to the fly," but Rocha is having none of it and just smacks him with leg kicks until Herzog tells the Aussie to stand.
Nicoll gathers his thoughts and spins with a back fist in the midst of a lengthy salvo of punches and knees, and Rocha's volume and power are giving Nicoll fits.
Nicoll's takedown results him in falling on his face, and Rocha blasts him with a soccer kick to the posterior.
Jason Jackson, eat your heart out.
Nicoll bites down on his mouthpiece to trade hands when getting back up, and Rocha welcomes this and smiles, throwing heat right back.
Nicoll realizes quickly this is not his best strategy, and as Rocha delivers a crisp punch to the midsection, Nicoll abandons ship almost entirely.
Backing off to try to protect himself, Nicoll retreats but practically allows Rocha to tackle him to the canvas so he stops hitting him in the stomach.
The horn sounds as Nicoll attempts a low-percentage leglock off his back.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Rocha Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Rocha Tyler Treese scores the round: 10-9 Rocha Round 3 The 125ers bump fists, but Rocha is bearing down on his opponent so Nicoll has to back all the way to the cage wall.
Rocha corners him and kicks him in the gut, and he lets Nicoll flail back so he can counter him effectively.
Nicoll plants his feet and drills Rocha in the chin with a check hook, and he lands a second while Rocha is a blender of feet and fists.
Rocha chains a stomping kick to the knee into a body kick, and he lets Nicoll advance to drive a knee directly into his jaw.
Nicoll has never been knocked out, and it shows, but he is under serious fire 11-plus minutes into this matchup and has little more to offer than a takedown shot.
Rocha drops to his knees and presses his weight behind Nicoll's neck to stifle the attempt, and he backs off and watches as a Nicoll right hand soars past him.
Rocha walks directly into a powerful right hand, and he is fired up and charges at the Aussie with several punches and a punishing head kick.
Nicoll doubles over but is not out of it yet, and Rocha jabs him several times to the midsection with his toes extended.
Rocha seemingly cannot miss when he commits to his punches, and Nicoll tries as he may to get the fight down.
When Nicoll finally completes one, "Fenomeno" phenomenally reverses him within seconds.
Rocha bashes Nicoll in the waist with a thudding right hand, and he backs Nicoll to the wall with punches and a capoeira kick that actually connects.
Nicoll applauds the blow and tries to give him something back in the form of a cartwheel kick, and Rocha dodges and holds up his fingers to show that Nicoll missed by "that" much.
Nicoll doggedly pursues his level changes, and Rocha turns the tables on him by bowling him over and climbing on top.
Rather than remain horizontal, Rocha stands back up and nails Nicoll with another flashy capoeira kick.
Nicoll grins, and Rocha grabs hold of him and takes him for a ride with his own double.
With Nicoll defending off his back using a kimura, time expires.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Rocha (30-27 Rocha) Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Rocha (30-27 Rocha) Tyler Treese scores the round: 10-9 Rocha (30-27 Rocha) The Official Result Lucas Rocha def.
Stewart Nicoll via Unanimous Decision (30-27, 30-27, 30-27)
Irina Alekseeva (135.5) vs.

Beatriz Mesquita (136) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Mesquita (-600); Alekseeva (+450) Round 1 The final women's match of the day comes at 135 pounds between a newcomer and a Russian who likely is on the last fight of her initial four-bout deal with the UFC.
Uber-talented grappler Mesquita (5-0, 0-0 UFC)âone of the best female grapplers ever, with more gold medals than Michael Phelpsâgets to ply her trade in the Octagon.
She faces a foe who calls herself "Russian Ronda," but Alekseeva (5-3, 1-2 UFC) only sports one armbar in her career to date.
What could be an interesting ground-based matchup will be officiated by referee Marc Goddard.
The ladies tap their gloves together to engage.
Alekseeva assumes the center of the cage, while Mesquita keeps a wide berth away from practically anything the Russian tosses at her.
Alekseeva gets off a jab or two, probing while the local contingent in the building call for her demise.
Mesquita introduces herself a minute in with a chopping kick and a right hand, and she scores another when rushing towards "Russian Ronda" for a clinch to takedown effort.
Mesquita presses Alekseeva to the wall, kicks off the fencing to creatively put Alekseeva on her back, and lands in full mount.
Mesquita sells out looking for a finish via strikes, beating on Alekseeva like a rented mule.
Punches and elbows continue to blast Alekseeva in the face, and a particularly harsh 12-to-6 elbow draws some blood on Alekseeva's nose.
The grappler has Alekseeva flat on her back, bludgeoning her with punches and elbows as she sees fit, and she calms herself down rather than succumbing to an adrenaline dump hunting for the stoppage.
No matter which way Alekseeva twists and bucks, Mesquita is comfortable on top of her making her day a bad one.
Mesquita considers an arm-triangle choke, snaking her left arm behind the head, but she instead unloads with blistering elbows as Goddard is watching quite closely.
The elbows have split Alekseeva open, and blood starts to pool in her eye socket.
Mesquita sits up and considers an armbar, but instead postures up with seconds to go to rain down hellacious punches and elbows.
Alekseeva somehow makes it to the bell, but if the second round goes anything like that, it may be a quick night at the office for the Brazilian.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-8 Mesquita Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-8 Mesquita Tyler Treese scores the round: 10-8 Mesquita Round 2 The Russian cleans up well between rounds, the blood all wiped away but her face undoubtedly showing some swellingâ¦everywhere.
Nevertheless, she works her way out of her corner and leads the dance with punches and kicks.
With Mesquita constantly circling on the outer edge of the cage, Alekseeva has time to chip and probe with distant strikes.
Mesquita clips her with a right hand, and she smoothly elevates and dumps Alekseeva to the floor effortlessly.
By the time "Bia" hits the floor, she is somehow already in half guard, able to take side control if she moves just a slight bit up.

Instead, her controlling posture shuts down Alekseeva, and she deftly advances to full mount.Alekseeva bucks and turns to her back, and the textbook rear-naked choke from Mesquita is almost instantly set up.
The grappling ace cinches her forearm beneath the chin without much resistance, and she rolls over to her back while leaning against the fencing to put as much pressure on the Russian as she can.
Alekseeva's arms start to show some slack as she stops fighting, and right before she goes out, her nose squirting a stream of blood in a less brutal version of Demian Maia vs.
Rick Story, Alekseeva surrenders.It was one-way traffic for the Brazilian, who makes a splash in her promotional debut and sets her sights on the top of her division.
The Official Result Beatriz Mesquita def.
Irina Alekseeva R2 2:14 via Submission (Rear-Naked Choke)
Thomas Petersen (246.5) vs.
Vitor Petrino (250) BETTING PREVIEW | SCOUTING REPORT | ODDS: Petrino (-300); Petersen (+250) Round 1 The big men have entered the building, and this contest could easily end in the blink of an eye.
Local fighter Petrino (12-2, 5-2 UFC) posts a 75% finish rate, but not to be outdone, the visiting Petersen (10-3, 2-2 UFC) has finished his opponent in eight of his 10 pro victories.
The fists are about to fly, and referee Joao Claudio Soares will make sure things remain on the up-and-up.
The heavy hands bump together before colliding into one another's mugs.
Petersen leaps forward with a left hand after they get their sea legs, and Petrino replies with a front kick.
Petersen punches his way into a takedown, and the former light heavyweight easily spins Petersen around in the clinch.
The grind is embraced until Petersen muscles his man around for a possible takedown, and Petrino hops around to get back into his preferred position and drops down for a single-leg entry.
The clinch allows the action to stall out, as Petersen gathers himself to pursue a single.
Petrino stops the first effort and the second as well, so Petersen ducks under to take his back standing and looks to pull him down from behind.
Petrino leans on the wire and keeps his legs spread to defend the dragging effort of "The Train," so Petersen goes after another single that also fails.
Petrino bounds away to reset, and he splits the guard with a destructive one-two that sends the American flying.
Petrino leaps after his opponent whose mouthpiece also flew through the air to try to finish the job, and when there is a moment to pause, Soares recovers Petersen's mouthpiece and gives it to him.
On the restart, Petrino hammers his foe a few times, and Petersen works his way back to his feet.
Petrino lifts and slams him down, but Petersen powers his way back up and hooks his fingers in the fence.
Soares tells him to knock it off, and he disengages but is still defending the takedown.
When the 10-second clapper sounds, Petrino abandons it and starts brawling.
Petersen gives as good as he gets, and the horn blares.

Sherdog Scores Jay Pettry scores the round: 10-9 Petrino Dayne Fox scores the round: 10-9 Petrino Tyler Treese scores the round: 10-9 Petrino Round 2 Petersen gets right into Petrino's face to start off the round, blocking a head kick and firing off two punches upstairs.
Petrino slides away, and Petersen chases after him hurling punches.
Petrino counters with a single, and "The Train" is not derailed by it and backs himself up to the fence to maintain his balance.
Petrino jams a knee or two to the body, and when Petersen turns him about, he nods to his corner and jacks Petersen in the jaw with a knee.
The Brazilian shrugs off a left hand as Petersen closes the distance again, and Soares is quick to separate them.
Petrino pump-fakes a few times to draw out reactions, and he puts a front kick between Petersen's guard to surprise him.
Petersen crashes after him to take him down, and Petrino grabs the fence to stay afloat and is fussed at by Soares but nothing else comes of it.
Petrino raises his hands at his opponent but might be keeping a solid poker face as he may be exhausted.
Petrino turns tail and runs away for a moment, and Petersen lets him get away with it but walks through a few punches to tie him up and shoot for a takedown.
The Brazilian defends one effort, and Petersen ducks beneath his arms to grab him from behind.
